<LP>
   A federal judge declared a partial mistrial in the case
against John A. Mulheren Jr. after a jury appeared to be
hopelessly deadlocked on 26 of the 30 counts against him.
   But U.S. District Judge Miriam Goldman Cedarbaum let stand
Mr. Mulheren's conviction on Tuesday of one count of
conspiracy and three counts of securities fraud.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Judge Cedarbaum granted a mistrial motion by Thomas
Puccio, the New York attorney representing Mr. Mulheren. In
that motion, which the government opposed, Mr. Puccio argued
that jurors were repeatedly asking the same questions and
that one of the jurors had indicated he planned a vacation
later this week. "Pressure could be brought to bear because
of that vacation schedule," Mr. Puccio said.
   The jury could not determine whether Mr. Mulheren was
guilty of conducting a series of trades that the government
alleged were designed to generate tax losses for convicted
former stock speculator Ivan F. Boesky's trading firm and to
help Mr. Boesky evade net-capital requirements.
   The government could retry Mr. Mulheren on those counts.
But E. Scott Gilbert, an assistant U.S. attorney who helped
prosecute Mr. Mulheren, said late yesterday: "We have not yet
made a determination on the extent of any retrial."
   The jury found earlier this week that Mr. Mulheren, 41
years old, conspired with Mr. Boesky to violate securities
laws. The jury also found that Mr. Mulheren had committed
securities fraud by manipulating the price of Gulf &amp; Western
Inc. shares in 1985.
   After the jury returned its verdict on the first four
counts, Judge Cedarbaum sent jurors back to deliberate on the
remaining counts. After two more days of deliberation, the
judge dismissed the jurors, declaring the mistrial.
   "I was quite surprised it ended like this," Mr. Mulheren
said yesterday. Mr. Mulheren said he believed that the Gulf &amp;
Western charges were weaker than others against him.
   Mr. Puccio said there was "no basis in law and fact" for
the convictions. Mr. Puccio said he planned to appeal the
convictions based on his theory that the jury had to find
only that Mr. Mulheren acted "voluntarily" in buying Gulf &amp;
Western stock. Mr. Puccio said that the jury should also have
had to decide whether Mr. Mulheren's purchase was intended to
help Mr. Boesky, as the government has charged.
   "John had no idea what Ivan was doing," Mr. Puccio said,
adding: "Gulf &amp; Western was the weakest part of this case."
   Mr. Mulheren's sentencing is scheduled for Oct. 5.
