   BILL TO CUT COSTS, DELAYS in civil lawsuits cleared by
Senate panel.
   The bill, approved 12-1 by the Senate Judiciary Committee,
would require each federal trial court to adopt a plan to cut
costs and delays. It also would create 77 new federal
judgeships, which congressional leaders say are needed to
clear huge backlogs in courts around the nation.
   The Judicial Conference, the policymaking arm of the
federal courts, says the provision on reducing delays is an
improper intrusion into the judicial branch of government.
The conference has advocated adding 96 new seats to the
federal bench.
   The bill received mixed reaction from federal judges but
has bipartisan support and is likely to be approved by the
full Senate. Judiciary Committee Chairman Joseph Biden (D.,
Del.) introduced the legislation jointly with the panel's
ranking Republican, Strom Thurmond of South Carolina.
   "For middle-class Americans as well as Fortune 500
companies, this legislation represents an important first
step toward reducing the costs and delays that plague the
civil justice system today," Sen. Biden said.
   The House is moving more slowly in considering legislation
to change the civil judiciary system.
   Some Democratic members of the Senate Judiciary Committee
went along with the Biden-Thurmond bill grudgingly, according
to people familiar with the committee. These lawmakers have
privately expressed surprise and anger that Mr. Biden would
lead an effort to expand the federal judiciary during a
Republican administration. The president nominates federal
judges, who must be confirmed by the Senate.
   For this reason, House Democrats are expected to push for
creating fewer new judgeships than are proposed by the Senate
bill.
