   SOUTH KOREAN UNION SUES U.S. company in labor dispute.
   In a move to enforce a labor contract overseas, the South
Korean union filed suit in federal court alleging contract
violations by a U.S. company's Korean subsidiary.
   The union's contract dispute with Pico Products Inc., a
Liverpool, N.Y., maker of telecommunication parts, sparked
labor unrest and a rise in anti-Americanism in South Korea
last year after Pico abruptly closed its plant outside Seoul.
The laborers -- who weren't paid for the preceding month's
work and weren't notified of the closing -- seized the
facility and accused the company of breaking its contract.
   In the suit filed in federal court in Syracuse, N.Y., the
Korean labor union alleged that Pico illegally closed the
plant rather than comply with the contract. The union,
represented by lawyers from the Center for Constitutional
Rights in New York, is seeking punitive damages, back pay and
other compensation, totaling $1 million, allegedly owed to
the workers.
   The suit claims that the contract obligated the company to
make compensation payments and to notify workers of the
closing. And in a move that could affect other multinational
companies if approved by the courts, the suit asks that the
1988 federal plant-closing notification law be applied to
U.S. companies' factories abroad as well as in the U.S.
   Bernard Hitchcock, Pico's chairman and chief executive
officer, said the contract isn't binding on the parent
company. Although the contract was signed by the South Korean
subsidiary in November 1988, he said the parent company never
approved it.
   "Pico Korea {the subsidiary} technically owes them some
wages," he said, but the parent company isn't obligated to
pay.
   Mr. Hitchcock also accused the union of kidnapping the
Korean plant's managers and holding them hostage until they
signed the contract. "I doubt that a contract that's gained
by extortion will be found to be binding," said Mr.
Hitchcock, who as of yesterday said he hadn't seen the suit.
