   EDWIN MEESE AWARDED $460,509 for legal bills.
   A federal court in Washington awarded the former attorney
general the money for legal bills incurred during the time he
was investigated by a special prosecutor. The U.S. Court of
Appeals disallowed $115,089 in expenses claimed by Mr.
Meese's defense lawyers, however.
   From May 1987 through June 1988, a special prosecutor
investigated allegations that Mr. Meese violated federal
ethics laws by helping Wedtech Corp. of New York obtain a
defense contract.
   The investigation didn't result in criminal charges being
filed against Mr. Meese. A close adviser to former President
Reagan, Mr. Meese left his post soon after the investigation
concluded.
   Under the independent counsel law, subjects of
investigations who aren't indicted are entitled to be
reimbursed by the government for what the court determines
are their reasonable legal-defense fees.
